National Burn Care Strategy
1.	Introduction

<mark>Purpose: Establish a national, resilient, and equitable burn care system that reduces incidence, mortality, disability, and socioeconomic impact.</mark>
<mark>Scope: Prevention, pre-hospital care, acute care, rehabilitation, reintegration, research, and mass-casualty preparedness.</mark>
<mark>Definitions: Burn care levels (Level 1/2/3), essential burn care package, referral criteria, mass burn incident.</mark>

2.	Vision & Mission
Vision: A resilient and equitable national burn care system that ensures timely, high-quality, and accessible prevention, treatment, rehabilitation and integration for all burn patients.
Mission: To reduce burn-related morbidity and mortality through integrated prevention, acute care, rehabilitation, research, and community support, guided by international best practices.

3.	Core Values & Principles
•	Equity & Access: Burn care available to all regardless of socioeconomic status or location.
•	Quality & Safety: Evidence-based, patient-centered, and multidisciplinary.
•	Efficiency & Sustainability: Optimal use of resources across levels of care.
•	Resilience: Preparedness for mass-casualty burn incidents.
•	Innovation: Adoption of new technologies, techniques, and research.
•	Rehabilitation & Reintegration: Supporting survivors to return to productive lives.

4.	Situational Analysis
~~• Burden of Disease: Current incidence and prevalence of burns nationally.~~
~~• Mortality & Morbidity Data: Hospital admissions, severity distribution, outcomes.~~
