~~• Gaps & Challenges: Limited specialized workforce, delayed referral systems, inadequate rehab services, weak prevention programs, financial barriers.~~
~~• Opportunities: Partnerships with NGOs, regional burn societies, donor support, telemedicine.~~
<mark>• Burden: Incidence, prevalence, DALYs, and geographic hotspot mapping by governorate.</mark>
<mark>• Case mix: Adult/child distribution, etiology (scald/flame/electrical/chemical), TBSA, inhalation injury.</mark>
<mark>• Capacity: Burn beds, ICU beds, OR capacity, rehab services, and workforce distribution by level.</mark>
<mark>• System performance: Time to definitive care, referral delays, infection rates, LOS, mortality by TBSA.</mark>
<mark>• Financial protection: OOP spending, catastrophic expenditure, insurance coverage.</mark>
<mark>• Gaps: Workforce shortages, inconsistent protocols, weak data systems, limited rehab/mental health.</mark>
<mark>• Opportunities: Universities, NGOs, regional burn societies, telehealth.</mark>




Strategic Goal
To reduce the burden of burn injuries and improve survival, recovery, and long-term outcomes through comprehensive prevention, high-quality specialized care, rehabilitation, and a resilient, evidence-based burn care system.

<mark>Strategic Objectives (Outcomes)</mark>
<mark>1) Reduce burn incidence by X% by year Y through risk reduction and prevention.</mark>
<mark>2) Reduce burn case-fatality rate by X% through timely access and standardized care.</mark>
<mark>3) Improve functional and psychosocial outcomes at 6 and 12 months post-injury.</mark>
<mark>4) Achieve national coverage of essential burn care services across all governorates.</mark>
<mark>5) Ensure national readiness for mass burn incidents within 3 years.</mark>

Burn Care Themes and Strategic Objectives
1.	Reduce burn incidence through prevention and awareness
о	Implement nationwide burn prevention and safety awareness campaigns targeting households, workplaces, and schools.
о	Strengthen community education on fire safety, safe cooking practices, electrical safety, and chemical handling.
о	Integrate burn prevention into existing public health and injury prevention programs.
2.	Strengthen specialized burn care capacity at central and subcentral levels
о	Upgrade infrastructure, equipment, and staffing of designated burn units in central and subcentral hospitals.
о	Develop and implement standardized clinical protocols for burn management aligned with international standards.
о	Enhance training and certification programs for healthcare workers involved in burn care.
3.	Improve survival and outcomes for acute burn patients
о	Strengthen early triage, referral, and transport systems for burn emergencies.
о	Ensure timely access to essential supplies, blood products, infection control measures, and critical care support.
о	Improve coordination between pre-hospital services and burn care facilities.
4.	Enhance rehabilitation and psychosocial support for burn survivors
о	Integrate physical rehabilitation, reconstructive surgery, and mental health services into the burn care continuum.
о	Establish follow-up and community-based support systems to facilitate social reintegration and return to work.
о	Strengthen family and caregiver support through counseling and education.
5.	Strengthen health system resilience for mass burn casualties
о	Develop and regularly update national and subnational mass burn casualty preparedness and response plans.
о	Conduct simulation exercises and capacity-building activities for surge response and inter-facility coordination.
о	Ensure availability of contingency supplies, referral pathways, and emergency coordination mechanisms.
6.	Promote research and innovation in burn care
о	Support operational research to improve clinical outcomes, cost-effectiveness, and service delivery models.
о	Strengthen data collection, surveillance, and burn registries to inform policy and planning.
о	Encourage partnerships with academic institutions and innovation hubs to advance burn care practices.

5.	Priority Areas / Strategic Pillars
The Egyptian National Burn Care Strategy includes six pillars, each includes a set of medium and long-term outcomes through which it can help achieve the expected results and contribute to achieving the desired impact.

Pillar 1: Prevention & Community Awareness
The aim of this pillar is to reduce the incidence and severity of burn injuries through effective prevention measures, public awareness, and risk reduction at community and institutional levels.
Developing the capacity of different sectors to communicate effectively with local communities, local partners and other stakeholders and gaining commitment and support from all different sectors is one of the main tasks to raise community awareness and engagement around the concepts burn prevention. This shall be achieved through the following Key Strategic Actions:
•	Establishing partnerships with national stakeholders and/or international organizations as part of the strategy to promote the concept of environmental safety and health protection.
•	Design and implement nationwide public education campaigns on fire safety, safe cooking practices, electrical safety, and industrial hazard prevention.
•	Integrate burn prevention and first aid education into school curricula and extracurricular activities.
•	Strengthen enforcement of national safety regulations related to housing, industry, transport, and hazardous materials.
•	Engage community leaders, civil society organizations, and media outlets to disseminate prevention messages.
•	Promote household-level risk assessments and community-based safety initiatives.

Pillar 2: Service Delivery & Clinical Care
This pillar aims to ensure the delivery of timely, equitable, and high-quality burn care services across all levels of the health system. It emphasizes health system reform and adaptation to enable effective preparedness and response to burn incidents, regardless of scale or severity. Strengthening system capacity to manage varying burn caseloads is a foundational objective of this strategy.
The standardization of burn clinical care pathways is a strategic priority, as it enables harmonized service delivery, informed planning for essential tools and resources, systematic capacity-building of healthcare professionals, and robust monitoring and evaluation of clinical outcomes. Achieving unified and high-quality service delivery and clinical care requires the implementation of the following Key Strategic Actions:
•	Develop and/or upgrade specialized burn units at central and sub-central hospitals, ensuring the provision of burn care through three defined levels of care aligned with case severity and surge capacity requirements.
•	Ensure equitable and needs-based geographical distribution of burn care services across all governorates in Egypt.
•	Establish standardized referral and counter-referral pathways for burn patients across the three levels of care to ensure continuity, efficiency, and quality of services.
•	Strengthen intensive care unit (ICU) capacity and critical care readiness to effectively manage severe and complex burn cases.
•	Integrate burn management protocols within national emergency medical services (EMS) and trauma systems to support timely triage, transport, and early definitive care.
•	Implement nationally standardized clinical guidelines for acute burn management and systematically monitor variations in care delivery and clinical outcomes.
•	Develop an integrated, multi-sectoral national plan for emergency preparedness and response for burn care in mass casualty incidents. 
•	Periodic and continuous evaluation of the readiness of preparedness and response plans, and to ensure their effectiveness, with a review of joint coordination mechanisms. 
<mark>• Define Level 1/2/3 burn services, minimum staffing ratios, ICU/OR capacity, and essential equipment.</mark>
<mark>• Establish national referral criteria (TBSA thresholds, inhalation injury, electrical/chemical burns, pediatric burns).</mark>
<mark>• Embed infection prevention, antimicrobial stewardship, and sepsis protocols.</mark>
<mark>• Require 24/7 access to blood, fluids, labs, and operating capability for severe burns.</mark>

Pillar 3: Workforce & Training
Human resources constitute a critical pillar underpinning the delivery of effective clinical care for burn victims. The success of this strategy is largely dependent on the development, deployment, and long-term retention of a competent, multidisciplinary workforce capable of delivering comprehensive burn care across the full continuum of services. 
The key strategic actions include the following: 
•	Develop a national workforce development strategy to strengthen the capacity of personnel across all relevant disciplines, including plastic surgery, intensive care, specialized nursing care, rehabilitation and psychiatry.
•	Develop structured national training curricula for all burn care providers—including burn surgeons, nurses, physiotherapists, occupational therapists, psychologists, and social workers—emphasizing evidence-based practices, standardized clinical guidelines, and multidisciplinary care approaches.
•	Implement mechanisms to retain skilled personnel in burn care services, including career pathways, incentives, and professional recognition.
•	Promote multidisciplinary team-based approaches to burn management, ensuring coordination across specialties and levels of care.
•	Establish tele-mentorship and e-learning platforms to support knowledge sharing and skills development, particularly in underserved areas.
~~• Conduct workforce planning and forecasting to anticipate future demand, including surge capacity needs and development of burn assessment teams and burn (BATs) and burn specialist teams (BSTs), and align training programs accordingly.~~
<mark>• Conduct workforce planning and forecasting, including surge capacity with trained Burn Assessment Teams (BATs) and Burn Specialist Teams (BSTs) for mass casualty events; align training and deployment plans accordingly.</mark>
•	Monitor and evaluate workforce performance, competency, and distribution to ensure equitable access to skilled burn care services nationwide.

Pillar 4: Infrastructure, Medicines & Technology
This pillar aims to ensure the availability of safe, functional infrastructure, essential medicines, and appropriate technologies to support high-quality burn care. Strengthening these foundational elements is critical for effective service delivery across all levels of the health system.
Key Strategic Actions:
•	Upgrade burn departments, units, and centers—including surgical theaters, burn wards, and intensive care units (ICUs) in designated hospitals—to meet GAHAR standards and the specific needs of burn patients.
•	Equip burn care facilities with the necessary medical equipment, expand access to advanced technologies, and implement comprehensive maintenance, calibration, and quality assurance systems to ensure the safety, reliability, and optimal performance of all health technologies.
•	Introduce new medications essential for burn care in Egypt and ensure the continuous availability of all critical medicines and medical supplies required for the effective clinical management of burn patients.
•	Promote the development and expansion of skin banks to support advanced burn care.
•	Strengthen supply chain management to maintain uninterrupted access to burn dressings, skin substitutes, grafting materials, and other critical supplies.
•	Establish telemedicine platforms to facilitate remote consultations, second opinions, and follow-up care, particularly for patients in underserved or remote areas.
<mark>• Establish national supply chain standards for burn dressings, grafting materials, and antimicrobials, including buffer stocks for surge events.</mark>

Pillar 5: Rehabilitation & Reintegration
This pillar focuses on closing the continuum of burn care by optimizing functional recovery, psychological well-being, and social reintegration of burn survivors. Effective rehabilitation and reintegration are essential to restore independence, improve quality of life, and enable full participation in society.
Key Strategic Actions:
•	Integrate early and long-term physical rehabilitation services into burn care pathways to optimize functional recovery.
•	Provide psychological support, mental health services, and peer support programs for burn survivors and their families to address emotional and social needs.
•	Strengthen access to reconstructive and corrective surgeries as part of post-acute care to restore function and appearance.
•	Develop vocational training and livelihood support programs to facilitate return to work and promote social inclusion.
•	Promote community-based rehabilitation and follow-up services to ensure continuity of care and support reintegration into society.

Pillar 6: Governance, Policy & Research
Effective governance is critical for improving overall performance, achieving strategic goals, and ensuring the efficient use of resources. Clear roles and responsibilities, transparent communication, evidence-based decision-making, and systematic review of processes are central principles of governance. Applied research and innovation are essential for strengthening evidence-based burn care and addressing key clinical and operational challenges. This pillar focuses on strengthening leadership, coordination, accountability, and research to support the national burn care system. 
Key Strategic Actions:
•	Formulate a national multi-sectoral burn care committee with clear terms of reference, roles, and responsibilities.
•	Develop strategies, policies, and standard operating procedures to support effective governance and coordination of burn care services.
•	Establish regular coordination mechanisms among stakeholders to ensure alignment and collaboration.
•	Establish national burn registries and surveillance systems to inform planning, resource allocation, and policy decisions.
•	Strengthen coordination mechanisms between government entities, partners, and academic institutions.
•	Promote operational research, innovation, and adoption of best practices in burn prevention, clinical care, rehabilitation, and reintegration. This includes identifying priority research areas, developing collaborative research proposals, and establishing partnerships, including funding agreements, to address critical research gaps and enhance the national evidence base.
•	Monitor and evaluate implementation progress using defined indicators and reporting mechanisms.
<mark>• Establish a national burn registry with a minimum dataset and mandatory reporting.</mark>
<mark>• Define accountability mechanisms: decision rights, escalation pathways, and annual public reporting.</mark>
Governance Structure:
The governance structure consists of two main bodies: the National Burn Care Steering Committee and Technical Burn Care Committee.
1. National Burn Care Steering Committee
•	Composition: High-level representatives from the Ministry of Health, Ministry of Law, Ministry of Higher Education, Ministry of Education, Ministry of Industry, and UN organizations including WHO and ILO.
•	Responsibilities:
о	Adopt policies and provide strategic oversight to facilitate coordination among stakeholders.
о	Approve national burn care protocols, operational plans, and action plans.
о	Facilitate allocation and continuous flow of financial and material resources for burn care programs.
о	Periodically review operational plans, assess progress, and propose strategic interventions to improve performance.
2. Technical Burn Care Committee
•	Composition: Multidisciplinary teams of senior technical experts from relevant ministries, institutions, and clinical experts.
•	Responsibilities:
о	Advise on strategic priorities and provide technical guidance.
о	Provide technical input for policy development, clinical guidelines, and protocols.
о	Formulate operational plans and coordinate implementation according to the strategic plan.
о	Facilitate partnerships to enhance implementation and ensure long-term sustainability.
о	Conduct periodic coordination meetings to address operational challenges and propose solutions.
о	Identify resource needs and coordinate allocation across sectors.
о	Facilitate information exchange and reporting among teams and partners.
о	Monitor and evaluate the implementation of burn care activities and programs.
о	Conduct regular meetings to review progress, address challenges, and propose solutions.

<mark>Service Delivery Model and Minimum Standards</mark>
<mark>- Level 1: First aid, stabilization, and referral.</mark>
<mark>- Level 2: Definitive care for moderate burns, surgery, short-term rehab.</mark>
<mark>- Level 3: Comprehensive care for severe burns, advanced ICU, complex reconstruction.</mark>
<mark>- Referral criteria: TBSA thresholds, inhalation injury, electrical/chemical, pediatric, and comorbidity triggers.</mark>
<mark>- Minimum staffing/bed ratios per level (including ICU and OR access).</mark>

6.	Implementation Framework
Roadmap / Timeline
•	Short-Term (1–2 years).
•	Medium-Term (3–5 years).
•	Long-Term (5–10 years).

7.	Monitoring, Evaluation & Learning (MEL)
•	Key Indicators:
о	Burn incidence rate.
о	Mortality and survival rates.
о	Average time to definitive care.
о	Functional and psychosocial outcomes post-treatment.
о	Coverage of prevention campaigns.
•	Regular reviews and reporting.
<mark>• Infection rates, sepsis rates, graft take rate, length of stay, rehab completion, return-to-work.</mark>
<mark>• Quality improvement: morbidity and mortality reviews, clinical audits, and guideline adherence.</mark>

8.	Risk Management & Resilience
•	Mass-casualty preparedness plans.
•	Stockpiles of supplies.
•	Simulation exercises for hospitals and EMS.
<mark>• Surge bed mapping, mutual aid agreements, and a national logistics plan for rapid distribution of supplies.</mark>

<mark>Financing and Sustainability</mark>
<mark>• Costed implementation plan with phased investments and domestic financing.</mark>
<mark>• Insurance coverage and social protection for burn patients and survivors.</mark>
<mark>• Pooled procurement to reduce costs and improve availability.</mark>

9.	Looking Forward towards Effective Implementation 
Burn care represents a complex health challenge for our society, encompassing a continuum that spans from community awareness and prevention to the social reintegration of survivors. Between these two stages lie numerous processes, interventions, and patient experiences that require coordinated, high-quality care.
The National Burn Care Strategy is structured around six main themes and strategic objectives, organized into six pillars, expected to be achieved over a ten-year horizon. To support implementation, the strategy will be accompanied by a comprehensive operational plan, providing guidance for all relevant partners and stakeholders to mainstream the planned actions.
Additionally, a robust monitoring and evaluation framework will be established, defining target outcomes and indicators linked to each component. This framework will facilitate measurement and reporting of progress, particularly during the initial five-year period of implementation. The strategy’s goals are designed to align with and contribute to the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs).
